If the problem changed from a binary tree to a ternary tree, we would need to modify the recurrence relation to account for the fact that each vertex can have up to three children. Let T_n denote the number of full ternary trees with n vertices. Then we can use the following recurrence relation:

T[i] = sum(T[j] * T[k] * T[i-j-k-1] for j in range(i-2) for k in range(i-j-2))

The intuition behind this recurrence relation is similar to the binary tree case. We can choose any vertex as the root of the tree, and then the left subtree, middle subtree, and right subtree must all be full ternary trees. We can then count the number of full ternary trees for each possible size of the left subtree (j vertices), middle subtree (k vertices), and right subtree (i-j-k-1 vertices), and sum them up.

Here's the Python code to implement this:

def full_ternary_trees(n):
    T = [0] * (n+1)
    T[0] = 1
    for i in range(1, n+1):
        for j in range(i-2):
            for k in range(i-j-2):
                T[i] += T[j] * T[k] * T[i-j-k-1]
    return T[n]

